                </a></li></ul></div><p><strong>Figure 1.  <span><em>Brenthia</em> moths are jumping spider mimics.</span></strong></p><a id="article1.body1.sec1.fig1.caption1.p1" name="article1.body1.sec1.fig1.caption1.p1"></a><p>The moth (upper image) mimics jumping spiders (lower image) with wing markings, wing positioning, posture, and movement (drawing by Virginia Wagner).</p>
<a id="article1.body1.sec1.fig1.caption1.p2" name="article1.body1.sec1.fig1.caption1.p2"></a><p>These moths survive encounters with jumping spiders more often than controls.</p>
<a id="article1.body1.sec1.fig1.caption1.p3" name="article1.body1.sec1.fig1.caption1.p3"></a><p>Moreover, jumping spiders respond to them with territorial displays that are normally directed towards other jumping spiders, indicating that <em>Brenthia</em> moths are being mistakenly recognized as jumping spiders, and not as potential prey.</p>
